			<item>
				<title>Kung Pao Chicken: The Stir-Fry That Made Sichuan Famous</title>
				<link>https://zhouyangimt.github.io/cuisine/kung-pao-chicken/</link>
				<pubDate>Fri, 19 Jun 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<guid>https://zhouyangimt.github.io/cuisine/kung-pao-chicken/</guid>
				<description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://zhouyangimt.github.io/images/kung-pao-chicken-1.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;Kung Pao Chicken — glazed chicken cubes with dried chilies and peanuts&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;There&amp;rsquo;s a reason Kung Pao Chicken (宫保鸡丁, &lt;em&gt;gōngbǎo jīdīng&lt;/em&gt;) sits on every Chinese takeout menu from New York to Nairobi. It&amp;rsquo;s not just easy to love — it&amp;rsquo;s impossible to forget.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-bite&#34;&gt;The Bite&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;You spear a cube of chicken with your chopsticks. It&amp;rsquo;s been velveted — bathed in egg white and cornstarch, then flash-fried — so the exterior has a whisper of crispness while the inside stays absurdly tender. The sauce clings to every surface: dark soy, black vinegar, a spoonful of sugar. Then the peanuts hit — roasted, still warm, giving you that earthy crunch right when your tongue starts registering the heat.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
			</item>
			<item>
				<title>Mapo Tofu: The Sichuan Classic That Conquered the World</title>
				<link>https://zhouyangimt.github.io/cuisine/mapo-tofu-sichuan-classic/</link>
				<pubDate>Fri, 19 Jun 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<guid>https://zhouyangimt.github.io/cuisine/mapo-tofu-sichuan-classic/</guid>
				<description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://zhouyangimt.github.io/images/mapo-tofu-sichuan.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;Mapo Tofu — silky tofu in a fiery red pool of chili oil and doubanjiang&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The bowl lands on your table and the smell arrives before anything else — fermented broad bean paste hitting a smoking-hot wok, garlic and ginger fried to the edge of burning, and a tingle-inducing cloud of Sichuan peppercorn that makes your nose twitch before you&amp;rsquo;ve even picked up a spoon.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Mapo Tofu (麻婆豆腐, &lt;em&gt;mápó dòufu&lt;/em&gt;). It is the dish that defines Sichuan cooking more than any other — more than Kung Pao Chicken, more than twice-cooked pork, more than hot pot. If you only eat one Sichuan dish in your life, this is the one.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
			</item>
			<item>
				<title>Peking Duck: The Dish That Fed Emperors</title>
				<link>https://zhouyangimt.github.io/cuisine/peking-duck/</link>
				<pubDate>Fri, 19 Jun 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<guid>https://zhouyangimt.github.io/cuisine/peking-duck/</guid>
				<description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://zhouyangimt.github.io/images/peking-duck-1.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;Peking Duck — glossy mahogany skin, carved tableside&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The cart rolls up to your table. On it: a whole duck, skin the color of polished mahogany, glistening under the restaurant lights. The chef works fast — &lt;em&gt;thwack thwack thwack&lt;/em&gt; — cleaving the skin off in neat rectangles, then slicing the meat into thin pinkish petals. The aroma hits you before the first piece touches the plate: malt sugar caramelized into glass, five-spice, wood smoke, roasted fat.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
			</item>
